{
  "text": "Limb-bud and heart (LBH) is a highly conserved tissue-specific transcriptional regulator in vertebrates with important roles in embryonic development [1] [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Aberrant gain-of-function of LBH, which maps to human chromosome 2p23, is associated with partial trisomy 2p syndrome, a rare human autosomal disorder with characteristic cardiovascular, skeletal and postaxial limb defects [CITATION_3] . Moreover, overexpression of LBH during mouse and chick embryogenesis results in dramatic phenotypes, including cardiovascular anomalies, impaired bone formation and angiogenesis [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
  "citation_candidates": [
